Class Element

  • java.lang.Object
    • lusc.net.github.Element

  • public class Element
extends java.lang.Object
    This is the object for elements, the smallest unit of sound measurement in Luscinia. Defined by a region on a spectrogram, elements have a range of different parameters, a definition of their range in the spectrogram, and a list of acoustic measurements.
    Author:
    Rob

      • getSignal

        public int[][] getSignal()
        This method returns the location of the element in a spectrogram as an int[][]. The first index should be even, and details start and stop locations of the element in the frequency domain (min freq, max freq pairs). The second index is the length of the element in the time domain. This allows fairly complex element forms to be stored.
        Returns:
        an int[][] detailing the location of the element.

      • setSignal

        This method sets the location of the element in a spectrogram. Not sure this is/should be used.
        Parameters:
        a - an int[][]

      • getPowerSpectrum

        public double[] getPowerSpectrum()
        This method returns a 'power spectrum' of the element, estimated from the power of the region of the spectrogram indicated by the element.
        Returns:
        a double[] where each value represents power at a different frequency bin in the spectrum.

      • getMeasurements

        public double[][] getMeasurements()
        This method gets the Elements measurements - a double[][] in which the first index refers to different frequency, amplitude etc parameters, and the second refers to the length of the element in the time domain. The array thus traces out trajectories of the various parameters
        Returns:
        a double[][] of acoustic trajectories

      • getStatistics

        public double[][] getStatistics()
        This method gets a range of summary statistics for each acoustic measurement of the element. This is a [][] double with length 9 in the first index, corresponding to the mean, median, variance, max, min, time of max, time of min, start and end values of each parameter.
        Returns:
        a double[][] of statistics.

        public void calculateStatistics()
